<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n34005b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n34" href="#n34005b">N34 (VI.B.27)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n34all.htm#n34005b"> 5(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bread &amp; wine</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Regeneration is offered by the word of God and in the sacraments, <i>which under visible signs communicate God&apos;s invisible grace to Christians when administered cum intentione</i>. There are <i>seven</i> mysteries or sacraments. Baptism <i>entirely destroys</i> original sin. In the Eucharist the true body and blood of Christ are <i>substantially present and the elements are changed into the substance of Christ, whose body and blood are corporeally partaken of by communicants</i>. <font size="-1">ALL</font> Christians should receive <mark>the bread and the <font size="-1">WINE</font></mark>. <i>The Eucharist is also an expiatory sacrifice</i>. <small> &ldquo;ORTHODOX EASTERN CHURCH&rdquo; <a name="EBOEC" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBOEC"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 336 [Comparison of Orthodox, Roman and Protestant doctrine [NOTE. Small capitals denote differences of the Greek Orthodox doctrine from Roman Catholic, italics differences from Protestant doctrines.]]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
